Xamarin Newsletter
November 2017

Save the Date for Microsoft Connect(); 2017

Join us online November 15-17, 2017 to hear from Microsoft's Cloud Chief Sc=
ott Guthrie, CVP of Developer Tools Nat Friedman, Principal Program Manager=
 Scott Hanselman, and other top developer minds. Connect(); 2017 will cover=
 the latest in open source technologies, Azure, Data, AI, DevOps, Visual St=
udio, Xamarin, and cross-platform applications, and inspire you to build th=
e apps of the future.=20

Save the date =C2=BB <http://mkto-o0039.com/v1SO0Qoi05dXJ3L5O04A000>


Upcoming Webinar: "Build Better Games with Unity and Microsoft Azure"

Join David Antognoli on Tuesday, November 7 at 9 am PT / 12 pm ET / 4 pm GM=
T to take your Unity games to the next level with powerful cloud services. =
You'll learn about connecting your apps to Microsoft Azure, adding compelli=
ng features (like leaderboards and heatmaps) that users love, and how new U=
nity and Visual Studio 2017 features improve your development process.=20

Register here =C2=BB <http://mkto-o0039.com/K00ASJO10doA435O305Q0X0>


Build and Release Five-Star Apps Faster with Visual Studio Mobile Center

The first step towards shipping high quality, five-star mobile apps is ensu=
ring the required tools and SDKs are properly installed to successfully bui=
ld the app and run the tests. Visual Studio Mobile Center allows you to set=
 up a virtual machine to help build your Xamarin mobile apps regardless of =
the platform, version, development technology, or form-factor targeted, as =
well as to run tests on that build using hundreds of unique, physical devic=
es.=20

Learn more =C2=BB <http://mkto-o0039.com/CO30040Bd1oJ0Q5O4A05X0S>


Try the Visual Studio 2017 Version 15.5 Preview

Visual Studio 2017 version 15.4 is now stable and sporting some amazing new=
 features, including Xamarin Live integration, Android Oreo / iOS 11 suppor=
t, and a smarter, smaller installation. The upcoming release of version 15.=
5 is now available as a preview, which, like all Visual Studio previews, is=
 a separate and sandboxed installation from your stable one so you can try =
it without worrying about your production development environment.=20

Try it out =C2=BB <http://mkto-o0039.com/x0J0000o4C51dQO055S3OXA>


Insider Tips for Getting Started with Xamarin.Forms Quickly=20

There=E2=80=99s always a learning curve for first time users of any new tec=
hnology or pattern. Xamarin.Forms Program Manager David Ortinau has gathere=
d feedback from first time users and curated helpful resources, including d=
ocumentation guides, Xamarin University training materials, blog posts, and=
 more, to help get you over that curve. Whether you=E2=80=99re new to Xamar=
in.Forms or a seasoned user, you=E2=80=99ll find something useful in his po=
st.=20

Get started =C2=BB <http://mkto-o0039.com/CO30060Dd1oJ0Q5O4A05X0S>



Tips and Tricks

Microcharts: Elegant Cross-Platform Charts for Every App: This guest post f=
rom Alo=C3=AFs Deniel, a Xamarin consultant at Orange Applications for Busi=
ness, provides an overview of Microcharts, a selection of ready-to-use char=
ts that are easy to use, visually pleasing, and built for cross-platform us=
e across Android, iOS, macOS, UWP, and Xamarin.Forms. <http://mkto-o0039.co=
m/NO00rJA500153oX0UQS0O4d>

Adaptive UI with Xamarin.Forms: Xamarin.Forms supports iOS, Android, and Wi=
ndows, which run on a wide variety of devices including phones, tablets, de=
sktops, and TVs. This blog post from Adrian Stevens explores how developers=
 can design a UI for Xamarin.Forms apps that intelligently scales and makes=
 sense on each idiom it=E2=80=99s presented on. <http://mkto-o0039.com/SO0X=
450Od1S0QJ30500oAVs>

Protecting Your Xamarin Apps with Dotfuscator: This special guest post from=
 Joe Sewell, a developer on the Dotfuscator team at PreEmptive Solutions, e=
xplains how obfuscation can protect a Xamarin.Android app from reverse engi=
neering, as well as how you can apply that same protection to your own Xama=
rin apps in a few simple steps. <http://mkto-o0039.com/E050J13WOtO0Q0AX4o0S=
d05>

Updating Xamarin.iOS Apps for the iPhone X: The new iPhone X Super Retina d=
isplay is edge-to-edge on the device, creating an immersive experience. Thi=
s blog post from Xamarin's John Miller takes a look at how you can start ge=
tting your app ready for these new screen changes. <http://mkto-o0039.com/C=
O300X0ud1oJ0Q5O4A05X0S>

